Passing a GPU through to a virtual machine (VM) in Proxmox VE for AI workloads 

    Access your Proxmox host shell via the web GUI or SSH.

    Open the GRUB configuration file:
    Bash

    nano /etc/default/grub

    Find the line that starts with GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT. You need to add intel_iommu=on or amd_iommu=on depending on your CPU.

        For Intel CPUs:
        Plaintext

        GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT="quiet intel_iommu=on"

        For AMD CPUs:
        Plaintext

        GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT="quiet amd_iommu=on"

    Save and exit (Ctrl+O, Enter, Ctrl+X).

    Update GRUB to apply changes:
    Bash

    update-grub

    Reboot your Proxmox server.

Step 2: Load Necessary Kernel Modules

Next, Proxmox needs to load the modules required for PCIe passthrough.

    Open the modules file:
    Bash

    nano /etc/modules

    Paste the following lines into the file:
    Plaintext

    vfio
    vfio_iommu_type1
    vfio_pci
    vfio_virqfd

    Save and exit, then run this command to refresh the configuration:
    Bash

    update-initramfs -u -k all

Step 3: Block Proxmox from Using the GPU (Blacklist Drivers)

If Proxmox tries to use the GPU for itself, it won't let the VM claim it. We need to tell the host to ignore the GPU drivers.

    Open the modprobe blacklist file:
    Bash

    nano /etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf

    Add the following lines (adjust if you are using an AMD GPU, but assuming Nvidia for AI):
    Plaintext

    blacklist nouveau
    blacklist nvidia
    blacklist nvidia_drm

    Save, exit, and reboot the Proxmox host one more time.
